Thanks for your call, my apologies I have been in and out (mostly out) of my office today, however it seems like everything is under control.
Enclosed is a
revised agenda. We look forward to meeting you topprrow.

As another component of the Bristol-Myers Squibb Graduate Fellowship program, we will provide a $3,000 annual stipend to Caltech in support of a seminar speaker of your choice. ask that the speaker be named the Bristol-Myers Squibb Lecturer in Organic Synthesis. option, we would also be pleased to send a speaker from Bristol-Myers Squibb to present one of our research programs.

Fellow to present a short talk on their research within the department. In this way, we could create an annual Bristol-Myers Squibb mini-symposium.
We look forward to hearing that the Graduate Fellow has been selected at Caltech and receiving the one-page summary of his/her research program.
Additionally, please let us know if you would
like to participate in the Bristol-Myers Squibb Lecturer Program and how you wish to structure the day so that we can send you the $3,000 stipend and, if desired, select a representative from Bristol-Myers Squibb to participate. If at all possible, we would like to hear from you by March 1,
The Bristol-Myers Squibb chemistry community believe this fellowship program will have a positive impact on the academic organic synthesis community. Through this program, we hope to encourage education and research in organic synthesis by providing funding to high-potential graduate students and support for high-caliber departments such as yours.
We hope you share in
our enthusiasm and will respond favorably to our intention to fund a Fellowship at Caltech. Please do not hesitate to call me if you have any questions.

My Background and Knowledge of the Field
-
I am a Professor of Chemistry at the California Institute of Technology
("Caltech"). I have personal knowledge of the matters stated in this declaration, if called upon to do so, I can and will competently testify to the following in a court of law.
I earned my Bachelor of Science in Chemistry in 1963 from the University of
Florida. I earned my Master of Science in Chemistry in 1965, also from the University of Florida. In 1968, I earned my Ph.D. in Chemistry from Columbia University. I was a Postdoctoral Fellow of the National Institutes of Health from 1968-69 at Stanford University.

Dear Professor Dervan:
February 5, 1998
As part of a larger funding program in support of academic organic synthesis research, we have established the Bristol-Myers Squibb Graduate Fellowship in Synthetic Organic Chemistry which will be initiated in the 1998-99 academic year. We are pleased to inform you that the Department of Chemistry at Caltech has been chosen as one of 10 departments to receive this award.
The goal
of this fellowship program is to provide support for growth within the field of organic synthesis.
The Fellowship is to be awarded annually to a high-potential senior graduate student of your choice whose research is focused on organic synthesis. The candidate should be among the top in his/her class academically and have achieved significant success in his/her research program.
$35,000 award will provide $30,000 toward the direct costs of the student's education and research, and $5,000 to their faculty supervisor to cover the cost of equipment and supplies. grant will be paid in one lump sum annually for three consecutive years.
Subsequently, Bristol-
Myers Squibb will consider renewing the commitment to Caltech for an additional three-year
We place two requirements on the awarding of these Graduate Fellowships. First, the award may not be used to pay indirect departmental and/or university costs. Secondly, we request the selected Fellow submit a one-page summary of his/her research to ensure a focus on organic synthesis.
As
indicated above, the selection of the Fellow will be made by you and your colleagues within the Department of Chemistry at Caltech.
At some point during the academic year, we will invite the Bristol-Myers Squibb Graduate Fellow from Caltech, together with the Fellows from nine other institutions, to one of our major research sites. During this visit, the Fellows will participate in a one-day symposium where they will have the opportunity to present short talks on their work, tour our research facilities, and participate in informal discussions with our staff.
We feel strongly that this visit will be rewarding to both
Bristol-Myers Squibb and the Fellow.
Consequently, we urge you to encourage the Caltech
Fellow to participate. Of course, all expenses for this visit will be covered by Bristol-Myers

Dear Bob:
Thank you for the time yesterday that we spent on the phone. We agreed to summarize our conversation in writing and forward our summaries to each other.
We learned Friday morning that Caltech filed a lawsuit in the U.S. District Court in Denver related to '108. We consider this to be counter-productive to our discussion on Thursday regarding how we might work together. In order for us to continue to conduct business negotiations we will need at least a 30-day delay in both the lawsuit filed by Caltech and the Arbitration Hearing. Additionally, we have obtained a formal opinion from counsel regarding the
*108 patent. Counsel concludes that the '108 is unlikely to survive litigation. A copy of the opinion is enclosed.
Returning to our Thursday teleconference, I would characterize our discussion as follows:
• You indicated that Caltech professors developed the technology and that you would like the catalysts to be widely available so that the capabilities can be further developed. Boulder Scientific Company
feels the same way. We want to make catalyst and be able to offer it to the chemical community.
• You indicated that you thought that a cross-licensing agreement with Materia would be a suitable solution. We agree with this approach and will continue to negotiate a royalty-bearing cross-license with Materia but only if the arbitration and the lawsuit are stayed by stipulation at least until April 8, 2002.
Finally, you observed that Materia has strengths in carly-stage catalyst development and Boulder has strengths in production and process scale-up. You also observed that this could form the basis for a successful cooperative business rclationship, and we agree. We would suggest that you and Materia provide additional details as to how such a relationship might work between the two companies.
I am looking forward to our continued discussion on Monday morning.
For Boulder Scientific Company

Chairman

Dear Bob:
Now that the Confidentiality Agreement is in place, I am sending you two reports summarizing of our work on Peach Twig Borer (PTB) pheromone synthesis, two patents pertaining to Gossyplure synthesis, and synthetic routes published in the literature on Gossyplure. As we discussed, I would like you to give some thought to a metathesis route to Gossyplure.
As the enclosed reports show, the PTB pheromone-synthesis results look promising. A catalyst-to-substrate ratio of 1:250 is viable, according to our economic projections. The reactions are run neat, which increases throughput and improves the economics. We have scaled up the reaction to produce > 100 g of PTB pheromone. This is the reaction we talked about that looked as if it reached equilibrium. We are within our economic cost goals, assuming we can get catalyst at $3200/kg and on time. We plan to put this process on the fast track for manufacturing.
We plan to start producing pheromone by August and complete optimization of the process after production begins. Key to using this process on commercial scale is availability of the catalyst;
we are working with Larry Gilbert regarding license agreements.
During our discussion regarding metal hydride formation, you mentioned that carbon tetrachloride terminates metal hydrides. I tried 24 mol% of a,a-dichlorotoluene (PhCHC1,) as a metal hydride terminator and it appeared to dramatically reduce the amount of terminal olefin isomerization. This is shown in the spectrum for Reaction 1392-157. In this reaction, 24 mol% (versus catalyst) of a,a-dichlorotoluene was used and reaction conditions were as follows:
1:250:500 ratio catalyst:chlorohexene:1-hexene, at 62°C for 21 hr under argon. A little isomerized material is seen around Rt 2.344 min (1-hexene) and Rt 4.535 min (chlorohexene), when compared with the spectrum for Reaction 1392-177, in which no a,a-dichlorotoluene was used. In Reaction 1392-177, we used the following reaction conditions: a 1:700:1875 ratio of catalyst:chlorohexene: 1-hexene, at 62°C for 22 hr under argon. The spectrum for Reaction
1392-177 shows large amounts of isomerized material at Rt 2.425 (1-hexene), Rt 2.528 (most likely 2-hexene), Rt 4.654 min (chlorohexene), and Rt 4.757 and Rt 4.822 min (most likely
1-chloro-4-hexene and 1-chloro-3-hexene). I am in the process of determining these isomers' retention times by GC.
From these two experiments, a,a-dichlorotoluene does appear to greatly reduce the amount of isomerized terminal olefin. I don't know if a metal hydride and a,a-dichlorotoluene react to

reform the starting benzylidene (Ru=CHPh)? Do you know of a clever way of testing to determine if the benzylidene is reformed and if this species is catalytically active? I am interested in your comments.
As we discussed, Consep is very interested in Gossyplure. Gossyplure is a 1:1 mixture of Z,Z-and Z,E-7,11-dodecadienyl acetate, and is the sex attractant of the pink bollworm, which is a major cotton pest. Consep's immediate problem is that the only two companies that produce Gossyplure are also Consep's competitors (Agri-Sense and Shin-Etsu). The price of Gossyplure keeps rising and there is some speculation that Consep's competitors think Consep has too much of the market share. Therefore, Consep is very interested in an economical, in-house route that can be used to produce Gossyplure.
I have examined the literature routes for preparation of Gossyplure via traditional synthetic chemistries, but I have not found a route that can be used to produce Gossyplure economically.
A route that looks attractive is Banasiak's patented metathesis route (which we believe is being used by Agri-Sense). Our patent attorney, Dennis Stenzel, informed me that the maintenance fees on this patent were not paid as of September 4, 1994, so this patent is in the public domain.
We could use this route if it is economical. I would like you to give some thought to the synthesis of Gossyplure using olefin metathesis catalysis.
If you have any questions, please give me a call. I will call you in a couple of weeks to get your input.
Sincerely

Update on the Peach Twig Borer (PTB) Pheromone Synthesis
Program
This letter covers work completed from March 15 to April 5, 1996, on the PTB pheromone synthesis program. The synthesis of PTB pheromone involves the coupling of 1-chloro-5-hexene and 1-hexene to yield 1-chloro-5-decene. 1-Chloro-5-decene is converted to 5-decenyl acetate and partially deacetylated to yield PTB pheromone.
Summary
During this reporting period, we made great progress on the PTB synthesis program. We ran a large-scale reaction and isolated 106g of chlorodecene, with an isolated yield of 38%. We increased the efficiency of the catalyst by a factor of three (i.e., producing three times the amount of product with the same amount of catalyst) and isomerized 10 g of decenyl acetate to an 80:20 isomeric ratio of trans (E) isomer to cis (Z) isomer. In addition, at the 50-g scale, we increased the number of catalyst turnovers by a factor of
We received a quote from Boulder Scientific to sell us the catalyst for $3200/kg. They indicated they can supply us with 50 kg of catalyst, which is enough for a 1000-kg PTB pheromone campaign. They are currently preparing a production and delivery schedule, which we will pass on to Consep and Farchan as soon as we receive it.
In another area, the synthesis of gossyplure, we learned that the maintenance fees on Banasiak's Gossyplure patent (U.S. Patent No. 4,609,498) were not paid, so this patent is now in the public domain and we can use this route if we chose.
Below, we summarize the work conducted during this reporting period.

Results During This Reporting Period
During this reporting period, we successfully completed a 100-g coupling reaction to produce 106 g of chlorodecene with an isolated yield of 38%.
For this reaction, we used
a catalyst:chlorohexene:1-hexene ratio of 1:250:500.
The reaction was run as follows: Chlorohexene (200 g, 95% pure) and 1-hexene (282 g) were added to a two-necked, round-bottomed 1-L flask containing a reflux condenser.
The solution was sparged with argon for 10 min. Catalyst (5.5 g) was added; stirring was then started and the reaction was placed in a 62°C oil bath. The reaction proceeded rapidly, as evidenced by the ethylene gas that was vented from the reaction into the hood.
GC analysis indicated that the reaction reached equilibrium in 3 hr.
After equilibrium was reached, the catalyst was removed by filtration through a small plug of silica gel. Chlorodecene (106 g) was isolated in 38% yield by vacuum distillation. This material was 99% chemically pure, as determined by gas chromatography, and had a 62:38 E:Z isomeric ratio. The chlorodecene was converted to decenyl acetate in 99% conversion and 95% isolated yield. A sample was sent to Denise, who confirmed the isomeric ratio and purity. Ten grams of this material was isomerized to an 80:20 E:Z isomeric ratio using thiophenol. Attempts to isomerize with iodine did not change the isomeric ratio. We plan to isomerize the remaining 96 g of decenyl acetate to the 80:20 isomeric ratio and send this material to Consep for evaluation and
As noted above, the reaction is rapid, reaching equilibrium more quickly than expected.
When the reaction is at equilibrium, the catalyst slowly dimerizes to form an inactive dimeric species. The easiest way to avoid this dimerization is to have a large substrate-to-catalyst ratio. Because the catalyst deactivation is a bimolecular reaction, decreasing the catalyst concentration decreases the rate of inactivation by a factor that is equal to the catalyst's concentration squared. This fact directs us to run this reaction with a large excess of 1-hexene (4- to 5-mole excess), which will shift chlorohexene to the desired product, chlorodecene, in high conversion.
During this reporting period, Boulder Scientific quoted us a catalyst price of $3200/kg and indicated they can supply us with 50 kg of catalyst, which is enough for a 1000-kg PTB pheromone campaign. Since most of our catalyst supply has been depleted, I would like Consep to buy some catalyst from Boulder Scientific, so that we can evaluate and test it using our new conditions.

Update on BRI's PTB Pheromone Synthesis Program
This letter summarizes the work that has been done in BRI's PTB pheromone synthesis program for March 1 through 14, 1996. The synthesis of PTB pheromone involves the coupling of 1-chloro-5-hexene and 1-hexene to yield 1-chloro-5-decene. 1-Chloro-5-decene is converted to 5-decenyl acetate and partially deacetylated to yield PTB
During this period, we have run two 10-g scale reactions and used the isolated yields from these reactions to project production costs for PTB pheromone. The timing for production-scale runs, at 100 kg/batch run, depends on the catalyst supply. We anticipate that process scale-up will be done at Farchan and then initial production could be done in their 250-gallon vessel.
In addition, work during this reporting period produced the following conclusions.

From these results, chlorohexene and 1-hexene ratios of 1:1 and 1:2 produced the highest yields of chlorodecene at 25°C (the last two entries in the table). Based on these results, we ran reactions using these two ratios at the 10-g scale. The results of these runs are shown in Table II.
Isolated yields of 42.0% and 27.0% were obtained. Note that unreacted starting materials and homocoupled products (i.e. decene and dichlorodecene) can be recycled back into the next reaction.
Chlorodecene is converted to 5-decenyl acetate by heating chlorodecene with 3 equivalents of potassium acetate, 3 equivalents of acetic anhydride, and 6 equivalents of acetic acid to 135°C for 18 hr. This reaction does not produce any new impurities, as determined by GC.

Insbesondere die Polymerisation von Cycloocten in wässriger Emulsion ist von ihm durchgeführt worden. Laut seiner Aussage ist aber auch Cyclopenten möglich. Cyclopenten ist ein Hauptbestandtell der C5-Fraktion des Steamcrackers und steht in grossen Mengen zur Verfügung. Das entsprechende Poly-Pentenamer wurde bereits von Bayer in den siebziger Jahren bis zur Marktreife entwickelt, jedoch nicht realisiert. Möglicherweise ergeben sich jetzt neue Perspektiven in wässrigen Dispersionen, vor allem aber durch die lebende Natur der Polymerisation (Blockbildung, Kettenende etc).

Ein weiters interessantes Gebiet ist die Herstellung von telechelen Elastomeren aus Butendiol und Cyclolefinen. Die Cycloolefine insertieren in die Doppelbindung und man kommt zu doppelbindungshaltigen Oligomeren mit definierter Funktionalitat. Das grosse Problem des reaktiven Kettenendes und des nur sehr schwer zu entfernenden Katalysators hat Grubbs jetzt durch die Zugabe von Vinyläthern gelöst. Diese reagieren mit dem Rutheniumkomplex so, daß er sich danach leicht entfernen lässt.
Wird dieses Konzept auf niedermolekulare Reaktionen angewendet, so gelangt man auf sehr elegantem Weg zu einer Fülle von cyclischen Olefinen, die sich als Wirkstoffe oder Duftstoffe eignen, und deren Synthese von einigen amerikanischen Firmen mit grosser Energie verfolgt wird.

Lebende Ringöffnende Metathesepolymerisation In Wasser
Besuch von Hr. Prof. Dr. Robert Grubbs, Caltech, Pasadena, California am 2.9.94 in Ludwigshafen
Professor Grubbs arbeitet seit einigen Jahren auf dem Gebiet der ringöffnenden Metathesepolymerisation (ROMP). Besonders spektakulär war vor ca vier Jahren die lebende Polymerisation von Cyclooctatetraen (aus BASF-Beständen) zu leitfähigem Poly-Acetylen.
in der Gruppe von Prof. Grubbs gelang es Bruce Novak schließlich auch, ein wasserlösliches Monomer in einer wässrigen Lösung metathetisch zu polymerisieren. Die Überraschung wer perfekt, da niemand erwartet hatte, daß eine normalerweise sehr empfindliche Reaktion unter derartigen Bedingungen abläuft. Es stellte sich sogar heraus, daß dieser Katalysator - Ruthenium-ditosylat - bei diesem speziellen Monomer sogar Wasser benötigte, um polymerisieren zu können.
Ru
L
Nun stellte Prof. Grubbs in einem Vortrag im Ammoniaklabor einen neuen Rutheniumkatalysator vor, der nicht nur das spezielle Oxabicyclo-Monomer polymerisieren kann, sondern anscheinend fast alle ROMP-fähigen Monomeren in wässrigen Systemen, d.h.
u.a. auch Dispersionen. Allgemein kann gesagt werden, daß man für die Polymerisationsreaktion in wässrigem Milieu zweiwertige Rutheniumverbindungen benötigt, die Cycloolefine mit grosser Ringspannungsenergie ringöffnend polymerisieren können.
Werden die normalerweise verwendeten aromatischen Phosphinliganden gegen aliphatische ersetzt, so werden auch Cycloolefine polymerisiert, die nur über eine kleine Ringspannungsenergie verfügen. Dieser Katalysator ist so robust, daß er sogar den direkten Kontakt mit der Atmosphäre in Pasadena überlebt (angesichts des L.A.-smogs laut Prof.
Grubbs eine beachtliche Tatsache).

Grubbs ist an einer Zusammenarbeit durchaus interessiert und er hat auch noch keine industriellen Partner auf diesem Gebiet. Er setzte allerdings seine Reise zur Fa.
Bayer/Leverkusen fort, die besonders an ROMP-Materialien als Polycarbonatersatz bei Compact Discs interessiert ist. Er hielt dort den gleichen Vortrag wie hier in Ludwigshafen.
Prof. Grubbs wäre prinzipiell bereit, einen BASF-Mitarbeiter für einige Zeit in seinem Labor mitarbeiten zu lassen, ihm dort die Katalysatorpräparation und anschliessend die Emulsionspolymerisation beizubringen, und ihn danach (nach 3 Wochen) mit einer ansehnlichen Katalysatormenge im Gepäck wieder nach Ludwigshafen zu schicken. Ich selbst habe das einmal während meiner postdoc-Zeit in Kalifornien von IBM aus bei ihm praktiziert und kann das nur empfehlen.
Zwei Möglichkeiten stehen zur Auswahl: entweder ein BASF-Forscher fliegt zu Grubbs, oder ein zur Zeit in Kalifornien befindlicher postdoc (der schon eine anstellungszusage hat) geht zu ihm, und bringt den Katalysator und das know how mit. Letzteres wäre billiger und schneller.
Dr. Wolfgang Maller, der zur Zeit in Berkeley ist und im März zu uns kommen wird, könnte das übernehmen.

The following are the minutes of a telephonic meeting of the Board of Directors (the
"Board") of Calhoun Vision, Inc., a California corporation (the "Company"), convened on March 27, 2014 in Pasadena, California. Directors James Adler, Jan Bonel, Javier Perez-Sala, Daniel Schwartz, Verne Sharma, Joseph De Vivo and Werner Wolfen were present. Director Robert Grubbs was absent. Also present was Richard Jones of Nixon Peabody LLP, counsel to the Company, who acted as secretary of the meeting.
Chairman Sharma called the meeting to order at 8:00 am, Pacific Time. At the request of the Chairman, Mr. Jones kept the minutes of the meeting. Chairman Sharma noted that the meeting had been called and noticed in accordance with the Bylaws of the Company, and that notice of the meeting had been properly given. Chairman Sharma stated that the purpose of the meeting was to discuss items contained in the agenda for the meeting, which had been previously
Chairman Sharma reviewed the status of the Company's fundraising, noting that the Company has issued and sold to shareholders Alex Furlotti and Alvaro Pascotto convertible notes in the amount of $2 million. He stated that Director Wolfen had raised an additional $250,000 in the Company's Series F Preferred. He briefly reviewed the Company's cash position and described several recent meetings with prospective investors.
Chairman Sharma noted that the transaction with Furlotti and Pascotto would not have been possible but for the willingness of Director Wolfen to exchange E shares owned by him for C shares owned by them. He noted that the C shares have a lower liquidation preference than the E shares, that the E shares are therefore more valuable, and that Director Wolfen should be compensated by the Company for his willingness to exchange his Series E shares. The Chairman proposed the grant of 40,000 options to Director Wolfen.
Director Schwartz proposed option grants for Director Grubbs, in respect of his efforts to develop a non-locking lens, which would enable patients to avoid wearing sunglasses. Director Schwartz noted that Director Grubbs has facilitated a number of improvements to LAL3 that are helpful for prospective commercialization. He proposed granting options to Dr. Grubbs to be issued upon the achievement of specified milestones. Chairman Sharma spoke in favor of the options and said that Director Grubbs efforts have been extremely helpful and would prove quite valuable when the Company moves to commercialization of the LAL. The Board directed the CEO to prepare an agreement between the Company and Dr. Grubbs in respect of such options and the conditions for their issuance and vesting.

Dear Bob:
Effective July 1, I will take over a new position with our parent company in Germany. I certainly have enjoyed our time in the USA, especially Pittsburgh.
This assignment allowed me to interact
and communicate with academia, colleagues from other companies, and with all levels here at Miles.
It has been an interesting time and I have enjoyed the experience in this very diverse environment with itneractions between the business side and the very basic research orientation in academia.
As you probably have already heard by now, my successor here at Miles will be Dr. Robert J.
Kumpf, who is committed to continued interaction with academia.
In my new position at Bayer as head of ZF-MFK (Central Research - Material Research Polymers) I will of course continue to cooperate with Miles and especially with Dr. Kumpf's group. It is our goal in the new Material Research Department to conduct R&D on an global scale. I would be happy to continue our interaction in the future. Dr. Kumpf's research group will be helpful in supporting future interactions.
In the future if you have any plans of visiting Europe, I would be delighted if you would let me know in time so we could make arrangements for you to visit our parent company if possible.

German / European Organic Chemistry Postdocs in the US and Canada
Postdoc Workshop
June 9 - 11, 2000
division of Bayer AG, Germany, invites
German/European
scientists in the US and Canada currently doing postdoctoral research in synthetic organic chemistry to participate in a workshop from June 9 - 11 in West Haven, CT. The workshop will be an excellent occasion to discuss highlights from Bayer's recent research in life sciences and to explore specific job opportunities. Over the next years, Bayer AG will continue to offer challenging positions in its Medicinal Departments in Wuppertal, and intends to recruit organic chemists with a particularly profound synthetic background.
Bayer's pharmaceutical research center in Connecticut will be the host of this workshop.
Located close to Long Island Sound, it provides a stimulating environment for scientific discussions.
Participants will have time to make personal
contacts with Bayer
representatives from the pharmaceutical, agricultural and central research divisions while visiting some of New England's historic sites and experiencing its unique cuisine.
Interested individuals with an excellent background in synthetic organic chemistry should send their résumés (documents for a German application: CV, certificates, abstracts of scientific research) until April 7, 2000 to one of the following addresses.
